\begin{slide}
\section{Dynamical Systems}

\begin{PauseHighLight}
  \begin{itemize}
  \item In the last lecture we saw that we could model the dynamics of a
    system of molecules $\bm{X}=(X_i|i=1,\,2,\,\ldots,\,n)$ in
    terms of differential equations
    \begin{align*}
      \frac{\dd X_i}{\dd t} &= f_i(\bm{X})\pause & \text{or} &&
      \frac{\dd [X_i]}{\dd t} &= f_i([\bm{X}])\pauseb
    \end{align*}
  \item These model the mean behaviour of a set of chemical
    equations\pause
  \item Provide the number of molecules is sufficiently large this model
    is accurate\pause
  \item In this lecture we look at mathematical tools for understanding
    sets of first order differential equations\pause
  \end{itemize}
\end{PauseHighLight}

\end{slide}

