\begin{slide}
\section{Stability Analysis}

\begin{PauseHighLight}
  \begin{itemize}
  \item If $\Re(\lambda_i) < 0$ for all $i$ the fixed point is stable
    (all sufficiently small perturbations shrink)\pause
  \item If there exists an $i$ such that $\Re(\lambda_i) > 0$ then the
    fixed point is unstable\pause
  \item If $\Re(\lambda_i) < 0$ and $\Re(\lambda_j) > 0$ then we are at
    an unstable saddle point\pause
  \item Note that the Jacobian is not symmetric which means the
    eigenvalues can occur in complex conjugate pairs
    (i.e. $\lambda_i^*=\lambda_j$)\pause
  \item In this case the trajectories will either spiral in to the fixed
    point or spiral away from the fixed point\pause
  \end{itemize}
\end{PauseHighLight}

\end{slide}

